{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4eb1f870-0766-4df2-b8c4-351a26fe1393","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for this project:\n\n## Evaluation Performance Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during **every evaluation** (design-time in VS, restore, build). This blocks the evaluation thread on disk access.\n\n**Fix:** Move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs during build execution, or use a custom task.\n\n### 2. Expensive Recursive Glob (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA `**\\*.*` glob walks the entire directory tree at evaluation time. If the tree grows (e.g., `node_modules`, large asset folders), evaluation will degrade proportionally. Add known heavy directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low-Medium Impact)\nThe import chain is 3 levels deep (`level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`). While 3 levels is still moderate, each import adds file-open overhead during evaluation. In a real project this pattern can balloon past 20+ levels and become significant.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The `File::ReadAllText` property function is the most impactful issue—move it to build-time execution. The recursive glob should be scoped more narrowly or exclude additional directories.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1706fba-724c-4d18-a46f-af9864ebf650","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"EC12:200D30:8012B5:9F8498:6A0130FB"},"id":"5cbeb601-90ef-4d83-bfb8-5c6784ffb76e","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:29:43.439Z","parentId":"1fc114d6-22bc-4ea2-8e92-857a336687ce"}
